name: East Gully
approach: King Ravine Trail to Great Gully Trail
description: A classic King Ravine gully with moderate sustained steepness and a narrow constriction near mid-line.

name: Great Gully (Lower)
approach: Short steep approach from Lowe’s Path.
description: Lower section of Great Gully featuring sustained climbing and a broad upper fan that can carry overhead hazard.

name: Iced Out
approach: Long approach via Lowe’s Path; requires alpine navigation.
description: A long, exposed line with variable snow surfaces and high wind exposure. Navigation skill required.

name: The Muffin
approach: Approach from King Ravine Trail.
description: A compact line that funnels into a narrow midsection, often with firm or thin snow coverage.

name: Narrow Gully
approach: Approach from King Ravine Trail.
description: True to its name, this gully tightens significantly and offers one of the more enclosed descents in the ravine.

name: Great Gully
approach: Approach from King Ravine Trail.
description: The main Great Gully route: wide lower slopes with a steep upper pinch that holds snow late into the spring.

name: West Gully
approach: Approach from King Ravine Trail.
description: A less-traveled western branch offering strong morning light and a slightly more direct fall line.

name: Baby Sister
approach: Approach via Castle Trail into the floor of Castle Ravine.
description: The shortest and most approachable of the Sister gullies, offering a clean apron and moderate sustained pitch.

name: Middle Sister
approach: Castle Trail to the central drainage of Castle Ravine.
description: The central Sister with a steeper midsection and more sustained climbing and skiing than Baby Sister.

name: South Sister
approach: Castle Trail then ascend to the southern fork of the ravine.
description: A narrower, more aesthetic gully with a steep upper throat and more technical feel.

name: North Sister
approach: Castle Trail to northern branch of Castle Ravine.
description: The longest and most committing Sister, with a rolling upper headwall and complex snowpacks.

name: Central Couloir
approach: Approach via Jefferson Loop Trail.
description: A long, straight fall-line couloir cutting through the center of Jefferson Ravine; steepest near the top.

name: Jefferson Headwall
approach: Approach via Jefferson Loop Trail.
description: The iconic headwall of Mount Jefferson: wide, steep, and wind-loaded with significant exposure.

name: Stealth Gully
approach: Approach via Jefferson Loop Trail.
description: A tucked-away gully with narrow rock walls and a steep sustained pitch.

name: The Beach
approach: Approach via Jefferson Loop Trail.
description: A wide, lower-angle gully with playful terrain and a more forgiving apron.

name: Airplane Gully
approach: From Great Gulf Trail, climb the main drainage until the obvious left-hand chute branches upward.
description: One of the most classic lines in the Great Gulf. Broad lower apron leading into a steep, striking couloir that stays chalky in spring conditions. A direct fall-line skier's line with great visibility.

name: Carousel Gully
approach: Follow the Great Gulf Trail, then ascend into the large central bowl beneath Jefferson.
description: A mellower-feeling Great Gulf line with playful terrain and a rounded upper bowl. Excellent mid-winter powder skiing when conditions align.

name: Drainpipe
approach: Ascend the drainage from Great Gulf Trail; Drainpipe branches climber’s right into a narrow rock-walled slot.
description: A narrow, aesthetic chute with the tightest walls in the region. True couloir skiing with a sustained, consistent pitch that rarely opens up until the exit apron.

name: Junebug Gully
approach: Leave the Great Gulf Trail near the central drainage and follow the skier’s left gully upward.
description: An approachable yet rewarding line with multiple terrain features, small rollovers, and a moderate upper headwall. Often skis well in March.

name: Mother-in-Law Gully
approach: From the Great Gulf Trail, trend climber’s right toward the larger northern faces beneath Jefferson.
description: A steep, aesthetic gully with a wide upper fan and a committing midsection. Less popular than Airplane but equally classic in the right snowpack.

name: Pipeline Gully
approach: Ascend the prominent drainage and look for the narrow central slot splitting the main face.
description: A tight, consistently steep line resembling a true couloir. Often holds firmer snow and requires strong edge control.

name: Stinkbug Gully
approach: Follow the Great Gulf drainage to a right-leaning upper fork beneath cliff bands.
description: A narrow, technical gully with irregular walls and multiple micro-features. Great for strong skiers wanting something more playful but still committing.

name: The Hidden Hallway
approach: Navigate toward the north-facing alcove above the drainage; the Hallway is not visible until deep in the basin.
description: A tucked-away and hard-to-spot line with a mysterious feel and maze-like terrain. Excellent snow preservation due to shading.

name: The Spacewalk
approach: Approach via the main Great Gulf drainage, then trend toward the broad upper ramp system.
description: A large, airy gully with sweeping open slopes. Feels bigger than most Great Gulf lines and offers dynamic fall-line skiing.

name: Turkey Chute
approach: Leave the Great Gulf Trail at the mid-drainage and ascend into the right-hand branch.
description: A fun, narrow gully with a playful midsection and moderate steepness. Often accessible slightly earlier in the season.

name: Turkey Feather
approach: Parallel approach to Turkey Chute, but branch climber’s right at the upper fork.
description: A slightly steeper and more direct sibling to Turkey Chute, with a firmer upper pitch and a tighter midsection.

name: Activator Gully
approach: Enter the Great Gulf and trend toward the visually obvious center gully beneath the cliff wall.
description: A dynamic line with rolling terrain features, strong overhead hazard, and a steep upper funnel. Very conditions-dependent.
